    <p style="text-align:center; font-family:'Open Sans',sans-serif; color:#555; max-width:680px; margin: -20px auto 40px; font-size:0.95rem;">
      When comparing storage in Vernal — whether you're looking at Fort Knox, AAA Preferred Storage, or any other option — these are the questions that reveal what you're actually paying for.
    </p>

    <div style="max-width: 820px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false">
          1. What is the unit made of — steel or wood frame?
          <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-a">
          This is the single most important question. Wood-frame storage units — the most common type in the Vernal area — can be physically chewed through by mice. If the facility uses wood-frame construction, your belongings are not truly rodent-proof no matter what their marketing says. Fort Knox uses sealed all-steel Cor-Ten shipping containers. Mice cannot chew through steel. Ask this question first, every time.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false">
          2. Are access hours truly 24/7 — or just most of the time?
          <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-a">
          Many Vernal storage facilities advertise "extended hours" but restrict gate access to windows like 6am–10pm. If you work oilfield shifts, farm early mornings, or simply need to access your unit at midnight or 4am, restricted hours are a real problem. Fort Knox has no access restrictions — your personal gate code works at any hour, any day, including holidays. Ask the facility: what happens if I show up at 3am?
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false">
          3. What is the total move-in cost — including deposit and fees?
          <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-a">
          The advertised monthly rate is often not what you pay on day one. Some Vernal storage facilities require a security deposit (one month's rent), an admin or processing fee, and first month's payment upfront — meaning you could owe three times the monthly rate before you've stored a single box. Fort Knox requires none of this. You pay the monthly rate and nothing else — no deposit, no admin fee, no move-in charge.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false">
